import java.io.File;
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory;
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilder;
import org.w3c.dom.*;

public class AttributeFinder {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      try {
         // Create a DOM parser
         DocumentBuilderFactory factory = DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance();
         DocumentBuilder builder = factory.newDocumentBuilder();

         // Parse the XML file
         File file = new File("example.xml");
         Document doc = builder.parse(file);

         // Traverse the document tree and find attributes and text nodes
         traverse(doc.getDocumentElement());
      } catch (Exception e) {
         e.printStackTrace();
      }
   }

   public static void traverse(Node node) {
      // Check if the node is an element
      if (node.getNodeType() == Node.ELEMENT_NODE) {
         // Get the attributes of the element
         NamedNodeMap attributes = node.getAttributes();
         for (int i = 0; i < attributes.getLength(); i++) {
            // Print the name and value of each attribute
            Node attribute = attributes.item(i);
            System.out.println("Attribute: " + attribute.getNodeName() + " = " + attribute.getNodeValue());
         }

         // Get the child nodes of the element
         NodeList children = node.getChildNodes();
         for (int i = 0; i < children.getLength(); i++) {
            // Traverse each child node
            traverse(children.item(i));
         }
      } else if (node.getNodeType() == Node.TEXT_NODE) {
         // Print the text content of the node
         System.out.println("Text: " + node.getNodeValue());
      }
   }
}
```

In this method, the `traverse` function recursively traverses the document tree and prints the name and value of each attribute and the text content of each text node. The `main` function creates a DOM parser, parses an XML file, and calls the `traverse` function with the root element of the document. 

Note that this method assumes that the XML document is well-formed and has a root element. It also assumes that there are no CDATA sections or comments in the document. If your XML document contains CDATA sections or comments, you may need to modify the `traverse` function to handle them appropriately.

