- When a new command is enqueued with the `enqueueCommand` method, the method first checks whether any commands are currently executing. If no commands are executing, the new command is executed immediately by calling the `executeCommand` method.
- If a command is already executing, the new command is simply added to the end of the command queue.
- The `executeCommand` method runs the command and then checks whether any commands are queued up. If there are, it takes the next command off the queue and executes it. If there aren't, it sets the `isExecuting` flag to false, indicating that there are no commands currently executing.

If the command execution throws an exception, the `isExecuting` flag is set to false and the exception is re-thrown, indicating that no commands were effectively queued.

