```java
public static double power(double base, int exponent) {
    if (exponent == 0) {
        return 1;
    }
    else if (exponent < 0) {
        return 1 / power(base, -exponent);
    }
    else {
        return base * power(base, exponent - 1);
    }
}
```

The `power` method takes in two arguments, `base` and `exponent`, and returns the result of `base` raised to the power of `exponent`.

The method first checks if the exponent is zero. If it is, the method returns 1 since any number raised to the power of 0 is 1.

If the exponent is negative, the method calculates the reciprocal of `base` raised to the positive exponent (i.e., `-exponent`) by calling itself recursively with the negated exponent.

If the exponent is positive, the method calculates the power using a recursive approach. It multiplies `base` with the result of `power(base, exponent - 1)`.

For example, to calculate 2 raised to the power of 3, you would call the method like this: `power(2, 3)`, which would return 8. Similarly, to calculate 5 raised to the power of -2, you would call the method like this: `power(5, -2)`, which would return 0.04.

