```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.ByteBuffer;
import java.nio.channels.ReadableByteChannel;
import java.nio.channels.WritableByteChannel;

public class ChannelCopy {

    public static void copy(ReadableByteChannel src, WritableByteChannel dest, int bufferSize) throws IOException {
        ByteBuffer buffer = ByteBuffer.allocate(bufferSize);

        while (src.read(buffer) != -1) {
            buffer.flip();
            dest.write(buffer);
            buffer.compact();
        }

        buffer.flip();

        while (buffer.hasRemaining()) {
            dest.write(buffer);
        }
    }
}
```

The `copy` method takes three arguments:

- `src`: A `ReadableByteChannel` that provides the source data to be copied.
- `dest`: A `WritableByteChannel` that receives the copied data.
- `bufferSize`: The size of the buffer used to transfer data from the source to the destination.

The method creates a `ByteBuffer` with the specified buffer size and enters a loop that reads data from the source channel into the buffer until there is no more data to read. 

After each read operation, the buffer is flipped to prepare it for writing and the data is written to the destination channel. The buffer is then compacted to prepare it for the next read operation.

Once there is no more data to read, the buffer is flipped again to prepare it for writing the remaining data to the destination channel. The method then enters another loop that writes the remaining data from the buffer to the destination channel.

