To create a Service Level Agreement (SLA) evaluator in Java, you can define a method with the following signature:

```
public static SLAEvaluator createSLAEvaluator(int maxLatency, int maxErrors);
```

The `createSLAEvaluator` method takes two parameters: `maxLatency` and `maxErrors`, which represent the maximum allowed latency and errors during materialization, respectively.

The `SLAEvaluator` class should have a method that checks if the current latency and error rates exceed the maximum allowed values:

```
public class SLAEvaluator {
    private int totalRequests;
    private int totalErrors;
    private long totalLatency;
    private int maxLatency;
    private int maxErrors;

    public SLAEvaluator(int maxLatency, int maxErrors) {
        this.maxLatency = maxLatency;
        this.maxErrors = maxErrors;
    }

    public synchronized boolean evaluate(long latency, boolean success) {
        totalRequests++;
        totalLatency += latency;
        if (!success) {
            totalErrors++;
        }

        if (totalErrors > maxErrors || totalLatency / totalRequests > maxLatency) {
            return false;
        }

        return true;
    }
}
```

The `evaluate` method takes two parameters: `latency` and `success`. The `latency` parameter represents the time taken to complete the request, and the `success` parameter is a boolean that indicates whether the request was successful or not.

The `evaluate` method updates the internal counters for total requests, total errors, and total latency. It then checks whether the total number of errors exceeds the `maxErrors` parameter or the average latency exceeds the `maxLatency` parameter. If either of these conditions is true, the method returns `false` to indicate that the SLA has been violated. Otherwise, it returns `true` to indicate that the materialization can proceed.

To create an instance of the `SLAEvaluator` class using the `createSLAEvaluator` method, you can simply call it with the desired `maxLatency` and `maxErrors` values:

```
SLAEvaluator evaluator = createSLAEvaluator(1000, 10);
```

This creates an SLA evaluator with a maximum latency of 1000 milliseconds and a maximum of 10 errors. You can then use this evaluator during materialization to ensure that the performance meets the defined SLA.

