public void dispatchAccessibilityEvent(View host, AccessibilityEvent event) {
    if (host == null || event == null) {
        return;
    }

    // Dispatch event to host view
    host.dispatchPopulateAccessibilityEvent(event);

    // Dispatch event to child views
    final int childCount = host instanceof ViewGroup ? ((ViewGroup) host).getChildCount() : 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < childCount; i++) {
        final View child = ((ViewGroup) host).getChildAt(i);
        if (child != null && child.getVisibility() == View.VISIBLE) {
            final AccessibilityEvent childEvent = AccessibilityEvent.obtain();
            child.onInitializeAccessibilityEvent(childEvent);
            dispatchAccessibilityEvent(child, childEvent);
            event.appendRecord(childEvent);
        }
    }
}

message:
Here's an example Java method that dispatches an `AccessibilityEvent` to the host `View` first and then to its children for adding their text content to the event:

```java
public void dispatchAccessibilityEvent(View host, AccessibilityEvent event) {
    if (host == null || event == null) {
        return;
    }

    // Dispatch event to host view
    host.dispatchPopulateAccessibilityEvent(event);

    // Dispatch event to child views
    final int childCount = host instanceof ViewGroup ? ((ViewGroup) host).getChildCount() : 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < childCount; i++) {
        final View child = ((ViewGroup) host).getChildAt(i);
        if (child != null && child.getVisibility() == View.VISIBLE) {
            final AccessibilityEvent childEvent = AccessibilityEvent.obtain();
            child.onInitializeAccessibilityEvent(childEvent);
            dispatchAccessibilityEvent(child, childEvent);
            event.appendRecord(childEvent);
        }
    }
}
```

The method takes two parameters: `host`, which is the host `View` that the event is being dispatched to, and `event`, which is the `AccessibilityEvent` that is being dispatched. 

The method first dispatches the event to the host `View` by calling `dispatchPopulateAccessibilityEvent()` on it. 

Then, if the host `View` is a `ViewGroup`, the method loops through its child views and dispatches the event to each child view. It creates a new `AccessibilityEvent` for each child view by calling `AccessibilityEvent.obtain()`, initializes the event by calling `onInitializeAccessibilityEvent()` on the child view, and recursively calls the `dispatchAccessibilityEvent()` method on the child view to add any text content it may have to the event. Finally, it appends the child event to the parent event by calling `event.appendRecord()`. 

If the host `View` is not a `ViewGroup`, the method simply returns after dispatching the event to the host view. 

Note that this implementation behaves as `View.dispatchPopulateAccessibilityEvent()` when no accessibility delegate has been set.

