```java
import java.util.PriorityQueue;

public class TopKSelector<T extends Comparable<T>> {

    private final PriorityQueue<T> queue;
    private final int k;

    public TopKSelector(int k) {
        this.k = k;
        this.queue = new PriorityQueue<>(k);
    }

    public void add(T element) {
        if (queue.size() < k) {
            queue.offer(element);
        } else if (element.compareTo(queue.peek()) > 0) {
            queue.poll();
            queue.offer(element);
        }
    }

    public T[] topK() {
        @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
        T[] result = (T[]) new Comparable[k];
        for (int i = k - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            result[i] = queue.poll();
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

The `TopKSelector` class uses a `PriorityQueue` to maintain the `k` greatest elements that have been added to it. When a new element is added to the `TopKSelector`, if the `PriorityQueue` is not full, the element is simply added to the queue. If the queue is full, the new element is compared to the smallest element in the queue (i.e., the element at the head of the queue). If the new element is greater than the smallest element in the queue, the smallest element is removed and the new element is added to the queue.

The `topK` method returns an array of the `k` greatest elements that have been added to the `TopKSelector`. The elements are removed from the queue in descending order and added to the result array. The result array is then returned.

