    public static String getJobOwnerGroupName(int jobId) throws IOException {
        String owner = getJobOwner(jobId);
        return getGroupName(owner);
    }

    private static String getJobOwner(int jobId) throws IOException {
        String procFilePath = "/proc/" + jobId + "/status";
        String[] statusLines = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get(procFilePath)).toArray(new String[0]);
        for (String line : statusLines) {
            if (line.startsWith("Uid:")) {
                String[] parts = line.split("\\s+");
                int uid = Integer.parseInt(parts[1]);
                return Files.getOwner(Paths.get("/proc")).getName(uid);
            }
        }
        throw new IOException("Unable to determine job owner for job ID " + jobId);
    }

    private static String getGroupName(String username) throws IOException {
        return Files.getAttribute(Paths.get("/etc/passwd"), "group").toString();
    }

}
```

The `getJobOwnerGroupName` method takes an integer `jobId` as input and returns the name of the group to which the job owner belongs. It uses the `getJobOwner` method to extract the username of the job owner from the `/proc/<jobId>/status` file, and then uses the `getGroupName` method to determine the name of the group to which the user belongs.

Note that the `getGroupName` method uses the `Files.getAttribute` method to retrieve the `group` attribute from the `/etc/passwd` file, which contains information about system users and groups. This method returns a comma-separated list of group names, so you may need to modify it to return only the first group name if the user belongs to multiple groups.

Also note that this code assumes that the program has sufficient permissions to read the `/proc` and `/etc/passwd` files, so you may need to run it as a privileged user (e.g., with `sudo`) to avoid `IOException`s.

