```java
public static double determinant(double[][] matrix) {
    int n = matrix.length;
    int[] indices = new int[n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        indices[i] = i;
    }
    return determinantHelper(matrix, indices);
}

private static double determinantHelper(double[][] matrix, int[] indices) {
    int n = matrix.length;
    if (n == 1) {
        return matrix[0][0];
    }
    double sum = 0;
    int sign = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (indices[i] != i) {
            sign *= -1;
        }
        double[][] submatrix = new double[n-1][n-1];
        for (int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
            for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
                if (k < i) {
                    submatrix[j-1][k] = matrix[j][k];
                } else if (k > i) {
                    submatrix[j-1][k-1] = matrix[j][k];
                }
            }
        }
        sum += sign * matrix[0][i] * determinantHelper(submatrix, Arrays.copyOfRange(indices, 1, n));
        if (indices[i] != i) {
            sign *= -1;
        }
    }
    return sum;
}
```

The `determinant()` method takes a matrix as input and returns its determinant. It first creates an array `indices` that holds the indices of the rows of the matrix. It then calls the `determinantHelper()` method, passing in the matrix and the `indices` array.

The `determinantHelper()` method is a recursive helper function that implements Leibniz's formula. It first checks if the matrix is a 1x1 matrix, in which case it just returns the single element as the determinant. Otherwise, it iterates over the columns of the matrix, calculating the determinant of the submatrix obtained by removing the first row and the current column, and multiplies it by the appropriate coefficient based on the sign of the permutation. It then adds up all these terms to get the final determinant.

Note that this implementation has a runtime of O(n!), so it is not suitable for large matrices. For larger matrices, LU decomposition or other more efficient algorithms should be used.

