```java
public static byte hash(byte[] key) {
    final int FNV_PRIME = 16777619;
    final int FNV_OFFSET_BASIS = 216613626;
    int hash = FNV_OFFSET_BASIS;
    for (byte b : key) {
        hash ^= (int) b & 0xff;
        hash *= FNV_PRIME;
    }
    return (byte) ((hash >> 24) ^ (hash >> 16) ^ (hash >> 8) ^ hash);
}
```

The FNV-1a hash function is a simple, fast, and non-cryptographic hash function that produces a reasonably good distribution of hash values. The hash function is computed by XORing each byte of the key with the current hash value and then multiplying the result by a prime number. The final hash value is obtained by XORing together the high-order bits of the intermediate hash values.

Note that the hash function may produce collisions (i.e., different keys may produce the same hash value), but the probability of collisions can be reduced by choosing a good hash function and ensuring that the hash table size is sufficiently large. Also note that the hash function assumes that the input key is not null and has at least one byte.

