```java
public void addAll(Iterable<T> elements, int k) {
    for (T element : elements) {
        if (queue.size() < k) {
            queue.add(element);
        } else {
            T min = queue.peek();
            if (comparator.compare(element, min) > 0) {
                queue.poll();
                queue.add(element);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Assuming that `queue` is a `PriorityQueue` that holds the current top k elements, and `comparator` is a `Comparator` that defines the ordering of the elements.

The method simply iterates over the elements in the input iterable, and for each element, checks if the queue is not yet full. If the queue is not full, the element is added to the queue. If the queue is full, the element is compared to the current smallest element in the queue (`peek()` returns the smallest element without removing it). If the element is larger than the smallest element, the smallest element is removed from the queue (`poll()` removes and returns the smallest element), and the new element is added to the queue.

The time complexity of this method is O(n log k) in the worst case, where n is the number of elements in the input iterable. This is because adding an element to a priority queue takes O(log k) time, and the method may need to add up to n elements to the queue. However, in practice, the amortized time complexity is closer to O(n), because most elements will not need to be added to the queue, and the cost of adding an element to the queue decreases as the size of the queue grows.

