import java.util.*;

public class TopKSelector<T> {
    private final PriorityQueue<T> minHeap;
    private final int k;
    private final Comparator<T> comparator;

    public TopKSelector(int k, Comparator<T> comparator) {
        this.k = k;
        this.comparator = comparator;
        this.minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(k, comparator.reversed());
    }

    public void offer(T element) {
        if (minHeap.size() < k) {
            minHeap.offer(element);
        } else if (comparator.compare(element, minHeap.peek()) > 0) {
            minHeap.poll();
            minHeap.offer(element);
        }
    }

    public List<T> getTopK() {
        List<T> topK = new ArrayList<>(minHeap);
        topK.sort(comparator);
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(topK);
    }
}
```

In this implementation, we use a `PriorityQueue` as a min heap to store the top `k` elements offered to the `TopKSelector`. When a new element is offered, we compare it to the current minimum element in the heap. If it is larger, we remove the minimum and insert the new element. By doing this, we maintain a heap of the `k` largest elements.

The `getTopK` method creates a new `ArrayList` containing the elements in the heap, and then sorts it using the provided comparator to put the elements in the desired order. Finally, we wrap the list in an unmodifiable wrapper to ensure that the caller cannot modify it.

This implementation runs in `O(k log k)` time, since we need to sort the `k` elements in the heap to return them in the specified order.

